english:
  title: Memorial Requesting Retirement
  author: Lee Gyeongbo
  language: eng
  text: |-
    Your servant Lee Gyeongbo humbly submits this petition. My years have reached the time for retirement, and burdened by infirmity, I beseech you to release me from office. Long have I blocked the path of worthier men, and keenly do I fear the weight of responsibility I bear. As my years approach seventy, what excuse could justify my continued service? In utmost sincerity, I beg to be relieved of these onerous duties.

    Reflecting upon my unworthiness: my learning has never been refined, my talents scarcely worthy of notice. Yet by rare fortune I have encountered this unprecedented opportunity, and my long-cherished hopes have been realized. My eyes scarce comprehended the mysteries of government, and yet my body now sits in the highest halls. For one of my station, no greater honor could be bestowed. Yet in this time of national crisis, I occupy a post for which I am unfit. I have not wielded cunning strategy to vanquish our foes, nor have I aided Heaven's transformations to harmonize the cosmic breath of yin and yang. My record is barren of achievement—only my stipend flows wastefully. Delay in my departure grows ever more shameful. What benefit lies in my remaining?

    Those who know my heart would counsel that I take my leave with grace. Those who seek my favor offer only empty comfort. Yet some whisper that by concealing my true years, I have deceived the throne's judgment. How could I expect mercy for this deception? My body withers—each step falters, each breath labors. My frame shrinks until it barely holds my robes. Should I force myself to remain in office, would not all point and laugh?

    Humbly I beseech the throne: let your bright illumination shine upon me, judge with resolute clarity, and grant me permission to depart. Let me taste the peace of leisure. Like one freed from a heavy burden, I shall devote my remaining years to preserving my health. Though I retire to my village, not a single day shall pass without remembrance of my duty to the realm.
  footnotes:
    - The 'Purple Pivot' (紫樞) and 'Yellow Pavilion' (黃閣) are classical references to the offices of high court officials.
    - This memorial reflects Lee Gyeongbo's actual request to retire from his position as Prime Minister, a common literary form in the Korean and Chinese official tradition.
